<br>
Since there seems to be a lot of envy going on here about charm soloing, I thought I'd add a little information.<br>
<br>
First off, charm soloing is very powerful - no argument there.  There are, however, significant drawbacks as well.  Most of which seem to be getting ignored.<br>
<br>
1.  You *always* get half-exp.  No enchanter is going to outdamage a charmed pet.  For those of you advanced enough to suggest AE mem-blur and nuke, yes, this technique works *occasionally*.  Blowing your mana this way just means you spend more time medding though.  And are you going to med with a charmed pet?  Decisions, decisions...<br>
<br>
2.  Do you die if you're not paying attention?  Sure, every class can die if you're not paying attention, but that oversimplifies the case.  A mage can gain exp without even trying (see - AFK camping, plzthxla~).  An enchanter charm soloing can become roadkill because they looked away for a second.  Literally.  That's more than just &quot;not paying attention&quot;.  That's &quot;keep your nose glued to the screen or die, chanter boy&quot;.  Even on normal exp camps, as my mage I've often sicced the pet and walked away from the machine to get a drink or something.  Try that charm soloing.<br>
<br>
3.  Sure, enchanters in *theory* have a lot of ways to regain control when charm breaks.  But the extensive list is only impressive to people that don't understand the process at all.<br>
<br>
Mez the mob.  Sure - this is generally the preferred method.  The problem is, mez lasts for 24 seconds minimum.  It's not unheard of for the charmee to break charm before mez breaks.  Oh, and while you're at it, you *are* crowd controlling your target, right?<br>
<br>
Root the mob.  Well.  Since the target is normally rooted as a safety measure, this doesn't do you any good at all.<br>
<br>
Stun the mob.  Two choices here.  If you use AE stuns, then everytime you have a charm break, you're going to get hurt.  Get a resist or a quick series of charm breaks, and you're hurt *bad*.  Quite possibly dead.  Alternatively, you could use your ranged stun spells.  Problem there is recast time.  One resist and you're kissing the pavement.  Again.<br>
<br>
Charm the mob.  No.  Charm is never a method of regaining control, you recharm *after* you regain control.  If you rely on charm to get control, well, I hope you have a rez stick handy.<br>
<br>
Which brings me to...<br>
<br>
4.  Death.  Death, death and more death.  I think this is why charm soloing is perceived as over-powered these days - most of the people complaining are discounting the downside of dying, becuase, well, you can always get a 96% rez, right?<br>
<br>
Maybe you can, maybe you can't.  I know that *I* don't have a rez stick at my beck and call...<br>
<br>
Charm soloing is a high risk, high reward technique.  If you have easy access to 96% rez, then much of the risk is mitigated, true.  But that could be said for *any* class which has access to a similar option.<br>
<br>
Mage pet soloing is a low-to-normal risk, low-to-normal reward technique.  BTW, having just passed 47, I can say with confidence that I can still take 2 blues at this time....<br>
<br>
5.  Speed.  Maybe this is a moot point to everyone but me, but charm soloing is considerably more difficult without some form of movement enhancement (SoW, J-boots, etc...).  Mages solo just fine without it.<br>
<br>
6.  Margin for error.  Maybe you never make mistakes, but I do.  There are far fewer *unrecoverable* mistakes you can make as a mage soloing, than charm soloing.<br>
<br>
I could go on and on, but why?<br>
<br>
...<br>
<br>
Class envy is *so* ugly. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ulumine.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lumine</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mage</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#333333>(5/15/02 10:50:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=207.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Charm is overpowered...</span><hr size=1> I've always considered myself an honest person. by this I mean, if something benefits me at the expense of someone else, I feel pretty uncomfortable about that.<br>
<br>
With that said, what I'm about to say isnt going to make some people happy.   I'm sure most Shadowknights aren't going to like what I'm about to say, but I'm sure most mages aren't going to give a crap.  But like I said, I'm honest, and honesty and fairness means more to me than not upsetting people.<br>
<br>
So I might as well say it:  my 47 Erudite Shadowknight is extremely overpowered.  I'm not talking about a twink SK with Primals and uber armor (which are also overpowered) either, but  a pencil-necked 140 STR Erudite SK with a MoSS and 910 AC.  In fact, there are really only 3 things in this game as overpowered:  every druid, Tumpy Tonics, and a certain level 47 chanter's jaw muscles.<br>
<br>
Let me paint a picture so you understand.  Yesterday in DL, my 47 Erudite Shadowknight fear-kited a ravishing drolvarg.  I snared it, dotted it, feared it, and ran around behind it hitting it with my mace until it died.  Then I killed another.  And another.  In fact, I kept on killing stuff like this until I had to camp for dinner.  After dinner (pasta primavera) I logged back in and kept doing the same thing over and over and over.  I felt awful.  I wanted to stop but I couldn't.  I cried out to the heavens &quot;Oh God, why hast thou made my Erudite SK so unbelievably powerful?!&quot;<br>
<br>
It gets worse.  I'm sure some of you are thinking &quot;Well youre only 47! I hardly think fear-kiting is that good later&quot;.  Well listen up, bub, 'cause I'm going to let you in on a little secret.  It's a little known fact that at level 50 the Shadowknights get a upgrade to their lifetaps from 85 hp to a whopping 300 hps!  And they can still FD like a necro, which means they can do all this at little or no risk!<br>
<br>
Why am I saying this?  Mostly my concience.  When I'm killing stuff in Dreadlands almost as fast as that goober over there, the idiot chanter with the hasted pet, I feel bad.  I feel bad that I can kill non-stop with no risk and negligible downtime.  And how am I able to do this?  How am I able to regen mana quickly enough to stay healed?  'Cause for 5pp the chanter  over there will cast clarity on me.  So it's not really me that's overpowered; without Clarity I can't get nearly as much exp/time.  So it's Clarity that's overpowered.<br>
<br>
Nerf Clarity.<br>
<br>
Thats all i wanted to say, <br>
<br>
Izzy<br>
<br>
Lumine, Phantasmist<br>
Jazborne, Blackguard<br>
Izzatyu, SK <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uryioko.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ryioko</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="Http://www.geocities.com/Jebabner/Bowser.jpeg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#333333>(5/15/02 10:58:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=207.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Charm is overpowered...</span><hr size=1> I don't think Charm is overpowered, because it has, in my opinion, a good Risk Vs. Reward.<br>
